model_answer: Sir Walter Raleigh was an English poet, sailor, courtier, writer, and soldier in the late 16th and early 17th centuries. He was a prominent figure in the Elizabethan era, serving as a favorite of Queen Elizabeth I. Raleigh was known for his exploration efforts, attempting to establish an English colony in America and leading expeditions to South America in search of El Dorado. He was also a prolific writer, authoring works such as "The History of the World" and "The Discovery of Guyana." Raleigh's life was marked by both great achievements and significant downfalls, including imprisonment in the Tower of London and ultimately execution under King James I. His legacy includes contributions to literature, exploration, and the early colonization efforts of England.
